Basic Heap Overflows
The basic theory for most heap overflows is the following: Like the stack of a
program, the heap of a program contains both data information and mainte-
nance information that controls how the program sees that data. The trick is
manipulating the malloc() or free() implementation into doing what you
want it to do—allow you to write a word or two of memory into a place you
can control.
Let’s take a sample program and analyze it from an attacker’s perspective:
/*notvuln.c*/
