Some exploitable coding errors in applications are the result of being able to
skip past the null-terminating byte in a string and continue processing into
undefined memory regions. Once the null-terminating byte has been skipped,
if any further processing results in a write operation, it may be possible to
cause memory corruption that leads to arbitrary code execution. These vul-
nerabilities usually surface in string processing loops, especially where more
than one character is processed at a time or where assumptions about string
length are made. The following code example was present until recently in the
mod_rewritemodule in Apache:
