structure with the address of the connecting entity [5], which eventually will
be copied out to user land. 
The size of the new sockaddr structure is compared to the size of the user-
supplied size argument [5], ensuring that there is enough space in the user-land
buffer to hold the structure. Unfortunately, this check is evaded, and attackers
can supply a negative value for the namelen integer and bypass this bigger-
than comparison. This evasion on the size check leads to having a large chunk
of kernel memory copied to the user-land buffer. 
